To interpret the visualization one needs to project the location of the city onto the individual attribute by drawing a perpendicular line to the arrow. The distance from the city to the arrow is meaningless and irrelevant for the interpretation. The only relevant thing is the point in which the line meets the arrow. \
\
For example, in the given graph, Brussels would be considered more clean than Vienna, because the point of intersection is closer to the tip of the arrow, even though it is further away from the arrow itself and the direction it is pointing towards. It is also worth pointing out, that the arrows do extend past the origin, so Geneva is less trendy than Vienna.\
\
